No, I understood that much, but I don't think you understood my response. Here are all of the 'error(...)' methods defined in 'Logger' version 1.7.26, extracted using 'javap' -- I have numbered them, so I can refer to them later:

 1) public abstract void error(java.lang.String);
 2) public abstract void error(java.lang.String, java.lang.Object...);
 3) public abstract void error(java.lang.String, java.lang.Object);
 4) public abstract void error(java.lang.String, java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object);
 5) public abstract void error(java.lang.String, java.lang.Throwable);
 6) public abstract void error(org.slf4j.Marker, java.lang.String);
 7) public abstract void error(org.slf4j.Marker, java.lang.String, java.lang.Object...);
 8) public abstract void error(org.slf4j.Marker, java.lang.String, java.lang.Object);
 9) public abstract void error(org.slf4j.Marker, java.lang.String, java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object);
10) public abstract void error(org.slf4j.Marker, java.lang.String, java.lang.Throwable);

I am not going to worry about #6 through #10, because we aren't currently using 'Marker'. Regarding methods #1 through #5, only #5 has the 'Throwable' argument, and I have been assuming that it is the only one that would print a stack trace from said 'Throwable'. That is the one I am currently calling. Note that it only has one 'String' argument, which is the message to be printed -- no space for {} here.

I assume you have been referring to one of the methods in the range #2 through #4, although I would have thought that the variable argument method #2 already covers #3 and #4, and even #1. However, I don't think any of the methods in the range of #2 through #4 would give you a stack backtrace -- you could only call 'Throwable.toString()' if you pass 'Throwable' as an argument, placing the output in one of the {} locations. Is there some trick to get a stack backtrace using #2 through #4 that I don't know about?
